lean_v_obese_pcoa <- Lean_v_obese1[, 2:596]

# Z-score normalization of numeric columns
lean_v_obese_normalized <- scale(lean_v_obese_pcoa)

# Check mean ~ 0 and sd ~ 1 for all normalized values
mean(lean_v_obese_normalized[,1])
## [1] 1.45603e-17
sd(lean_v_obese_normalized[,1])
## [1] 1
#Convert status column to factor
Lean_v_obese1$Status <- as.factor(Lean_v_obese1$Status)

3. Principle Coordinate Analysis:

# Calculating distance matrix
distance_matrix_lvo <- dist(lean_v_obese_normalized, method = "euclidean")

# PCoA, using Euclidean distance, 2 principal coordinates
pcoa_results_norm <- cmdscale(distance_matrix_lvo, eig = TRUE, k = 2)

# Extract eigenvalues
eigenvalues <- pcoa_results_norm$eig

# Calculate variance explained by each coordinate axis
variance_explained <- eigenvalues / sum(eigenvalues) * 100
pcoa1_var <- round(variance_explained[1], 2)  # Variance explained by PCoA1
pcoa2_var <- round(variance_explained[2], 2)  # Variance explained by PCoA2

# Cumulative variance explained plot
total_variance_explained <- cumsum(eigenvalues) / sum(eigenvalues)
plot(total_variance_explained, type = "b", xlab = "Number of Dimensions", ylab = "Cumulative Variance Explained",
     main = "Cumulative Variance Explained by PCoA Dimensions")
abline(h = 0.36, v = 2, col = "red", lty = 2)  

# Creating dataframe for coordinates for each sample in PCoA space
pcoa_df_norm <- as.data.frame(pcoa_results_norm$points)

# Add status column to dataframe containing cooordinates for PCoA
pcoa_df_norm$Status <- Lean_v_obese1$Status

3.1 PERMANOVA Test:

# PERMANOVA to test significance between lean vs obese
permanova_results <- adonis2(distance_matrix_lvo ~ Lean_v_obese1$Status, data = Lean_v_obese1, permutations = 999)

# Extract p and R2 values
p_value <- permanova_results$`Pr(>F)`[1]
print(p_value)
## [1] 0.001
R_squared <- permanova_results$R2[1]
print(R_squared)
## [1] 0.1005009
# Scree plot to determine the number of dimensions
plot(eigenvalues, type = "b", xlab = "Dimension", ylab = "Eigenvalue", main = "Scree Plot")

# Visualization of PCoA results
ggplot(pcoa_df_norm, aes(x = V1, y = V2, color = Status)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3) + 
  stat_ellipse(type = "t", level = 0.95) + 
  labs(title = "Principal Coordinate Analysis (Euclidean Distance)",
       x = paste0("PCoA1 (", pcoa1_var, "% variance)"),
       y = paste0("PCoA2 (", pcoa2_var, "% variance)")) + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12)) +
  annotate("text", x = -10, y = 15, 
           label = paste("p-value =", round(p_value, 4), "\nR² =", round(R_squared, 4)), 
           size = 4, hjust = 0) + 
  theme_classic()

4. Classification Random forest model: predicting status

4.1 Build random forest model

#Step 1: Preparing training dataset
 predict_lvo <- Lean_v_obese[, 2:596]

#Step 2: Preparing response variables
 res_lvo <- Lean_v_obese$Status 
 
#Step 3: Combining predicting and response dataset
 machine_data_lvo <- data.frame(res_lvo, predict_lvo)

#Standardise column names
colnames(machine_data_lvo) <- make.names(colnames(machine_data_lvo))
 
#Step 4: Convert response variable to factor
 machine_data_lvo$res_lvo <- as.factor(machine_data_lvo$res_lvo)
 
#Step 5: Set Reproducibility
 set.seed(8)
 
#Step 6: Random forest
 class_lvo_rf <- randomForest(res_lvo ~ ., data= machine_data_lvo, ntree=1000, importance= TRUE)
 print(class_lvo_rf)

4.2 Extracting important features from model

#Extract important feature from RF model: Important lipids as predictors
imp_lvo <- importance(class_lvo_rf)
 
#order the lipids according to the values in the "MeanDecreaseAccuracy" column, in decreasing order.
Ordered_imp_lvo <- imp_lvo[order(imp_lvo[, "MeanDecreaseAccuracy"], decreasing= TRUE), ]

#Convert to dataframe
Ordered_imp_lvo <- as.data.frame(Ordered_imp_lvo)
 
#Assign respective lipids names
Ordered_imp_lvo <- cbind(Compound=rownames(Ordered_imp_lvo), Ordered_imp_lvo)
 
#top 20 important lipids
Ordered_imp_lvo_20 <- head(Ordered_imp_lvo, 20)
 
#top 10 important lipids
Ordered_imp_lvo_10 <- head(Ordered_imp_lvo, 10)
 
#Visualisation: Top 10 lipids in order of mean decrease accuracy
ggplot(Ordered_imp_lvo_10, aes(x= reorder(Compound, MeanDecreaseAccuracy,decreasing= TRUE), y =   MeanDecreaseAccuracy,fill="Compound"))+
   geom_bar(stat="identity")+
   coord_flip()+
   theme_classic()+
   theme(legend.position="none",  
    plot.title = element_text(size = 10, hjust = 1), axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black")) + 
   labs(x="Lipids", y="Total Mean Decrease Accuracy")

4.4 Wilcoxon rank- sum test to test significant difference

 # Initialize a list to store results, stringsAsFactors for character not converted to factors
results <- data.frame(Lipid = character(), p_value = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# perform the Wilcoxon rank-sum test for each unique lipid (Lipid) to compare the Value between the two Status groups
wilcoxon_results <- pivoted_top_20_data %>%
  group_by(Lipid) %>%
  summarise(p_value = wilcox.test(Value ~ Status)$p.value)
print((wilcoxon_results))

6. KNN model: predicting Status

#Assign predicting variable:
 predict_lvo_knn <- log2_norm_lean_v_obese[, 2:596]
 
#response variable
 res_lvo_knn<- log2_norm_lean_v_obese$Status
 
#Merge predicting and rsponse variable in one dataframe
 machine_data_lvo_knn <- data.frame(res_lvo_knn, predict_lvo_knn)
 
#Name of columns got changed, so assigning these names to their original(reference:predict_lvo_knn1)
colnames(machine_data_lvo_knn)[-1] <- colnames(predict_lvo_knn)
 
#Converting response variable column to factor
machine_data_lvo_knn$res_lvo_knn <- factor(machine_data_lvo_knn$res_lvo_knn, levels=c("Lean","Obese"))
 
#Splitting the data into training set and testing sets
set.seed(100) #for reproducibility
 
trainIndex_lvo <- createDataPartition (machine_data_lvo_knn$res_lvo_knn, p=0.8, list=F)
trainData_lvo_knn <- machine_data_lvo_knn[trainIndex_lvo, ]
testData_lvo_knn <-  machine_data_lvo_knn[-trainIndex_lvo, ]
 
#Define the training control:Crossvalidation
train_control_lvo_knn <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)
 
#Define values for k (number of neighbors)
 tune_k <- expand.grid(k = seq(1, 20, by = 2))  # Test odd k values from 1 to 20
 
# Train the KNN model with hyperparameter tuning
 knn_lvo <- caret::train(res_lvo_knn ~ ., 
   data = trainData_lvo_knn,
   method = "knn",
   trControl = train_control_lvo_knn,
   tuneGrid = tune_k)
 
 # Print the results of the tuning
 print(knn_lvo)

## 
## Accuracy was used to select the optimal model using the largest value.
## The final value used for the model was k = 13.
 # View the best k value
 knn_lvo$bestTune
##    k
## 7 13
 # Plot the accuracy for different k values
 plot(knn_lvo, xlab="Number of neighbours")

6.1 Confusion matrix for KNN model: evaluate the model’s performance on a test dataset

#Generate predictions from our trained KNN model
predictions_lvo<-  predict (knn_lvo, newdata = testData_lvo_knn)

#Compute confusion matrix
cm <- confusionMatrix(predictions_lvo, testData_lvo_knn$res_lvo_knn)
print(cm)

6.2 Area Under Curve(AUC) and Receiver Operating Characteristics(ROC): metrics for model evaluation

#Making predictions on the test set, predicting levels and probabilities of samples belonging to that class
knn_prediction <- predict(knn_lvo, newdata=testData_lvo_knn, type="prob")
 
#True labels for the test data: actual categories assigned to each sample. In our case:Lean and obese
original_labels <- testData_lvo_knn$res_lvo_knn

# ROC Curve: original labels and the predicted probabilities for the positive class as inputs.
ROC_curve <- pROC::roc(original_labels, knn_prediction[, 2])  
## Setting levels: control = Lean, case = Obese
## Setting direction: controls < cases
#Calculate TPR or FPR :TPR= sensitivity, FPR= 1-Specificity
ROC_df <- data.frame(TPR = ROC_curve$sensitivities, FPR = 1 - ROC_curve$specificities)

#Visualization:
plot(ROC_df$FPR, ROC_df$TPR, type="l", col="blue", lwd=2, xlab="False Positive Rate(1-Specificity)",        ylab="True Positive Rate(Sensitivity)", 
      main="ROC and AUC for KNN Model (Lean vs Obese)")
      grid()
      points(ROC_df$FPR, ROC_df$TPR, col="blue", pch=16)
      abline(a=0, b=1, col="red", lty=2, lwd=2)# Add a diagonal line representing the threshold of 0.5
      legend("bottomright", 
        legend=c("ROC Curve", 
                 "Threshold = 0.5", 
                 paste("AUC =",round(pROC::auc(ROC_curve), 2))),  
        col=c("blue", "red"), 
        lty=c(1, 2), #line type
        lwd=2)       #line width

1. Regression random forest model: predicting BMI

1.1 Data preparation:

#import metadata
metadata <- read.csv("modified_bariatric_metadata.csv")

#Merging dataframe with metdata
#Import sample ID information
 sampleID <- read_excel("ID_lvo.xlsx")

#extract unique sample ID from metadata corresponding Day 0:sample collection
 unique_ID <- metadata %>%
   filter(Days_Elapsed == 0) %>%
   distinct(ParticipantID, .keep_all = TRUE)
 
#merge two dataframe
 merged_lvo <- merge(unique_ID, sampleID, by = "ParticipantID", all.x = TRUE)

#Modifiying sample id as 1424-1(raw) from 1424-1 to match column value in 2 database for merging    
 merged_lvo$`Sample ID` <- paste0(merged_lvo$`Sample ID`, "(raw)")
 
#Merging lean_v_obese original dataframe to metadata derived merged_df
lvo <- subset(Lean_v_obese, select = -Status)
final_lvo_metadata <- merge(lvo, merged_lvo, by = "Sample ID", all.x = TRUE)

1.2 Build the regression Random Forest model:

#Preparing training dataset:
 train_meta <- final_lvo_metadata[, 2:596]

#Preparing response variables
 res_meta <- final_lvo_metadata$BMI..kg.m2.
 
#Combining predicting and response dataset
 machine_meta <- data.frame(res_meta, train_meta)
 
#Convert "#VALUE!" in dataset to NA
 machine_meta[machine_meta == "#VALUE!"] <- NA
 machine_meta[machine_meta == ""] <- NA
 
#Assign colnames to their original ones
colnames(machine_meta) <- make.names(colnames(machine_meta))

#Reproducibility
set.seed(1000)
 
#response variable should be numeric for regression model
machine_meta$res_meta <- as.numeric(machine_meta$res_meta)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
#Remove NAs
machine_meta <- na.omit(machine_meta)
 
#Regression Random forest
regression_rf_bmi<- randomForest(res_meta ~ ., data= machine_meta, ntree=1000, importance= TRUE)
print(regression_rf_bmi)
## 
## Call:

#Import important feature
imp_bmi <- importance(regression_rf_bmi)

#Convert percent increase in mean standard error to numeric

2 Multiclass classification Random forest model to predict class of BMI:

2.1 Data preparation

final_meta <- final_lvo_metadata
 
#Identifying class of BMI on basis of their values:
final_meta$BMI_class <- ifelse(final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. <18.5, "Underweight",
                        ifelse(final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. >= 18.5 & final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. < 24.9, "Normal Weight",
                        ifelse(final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. >= 25 & final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. < 29.9, "Class 1 Obese", 
                        ifelse(final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. >= 30 & final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. < 34.9, "Class 2 Obese",
                        ifelse(final_meta$BMI..kg.m2. >= 40, "Class 3 obese",NA)))))

2.2 Building multiclass Random Forest model:

 #Preparing training dataset:
 predict_set <- final_meta[, 2:596]
 
 #Preparing response variables
 res_set <- final_meta$BMI_class
 
 #Combining predicting and response dataset
 machine_bmi <- data.frame(res_set, predict_set)

 #colnames(machine_data_lvo)[-1] <- colnames(predict_lvo)
 colnames(machine_bmi) <- make.names(colnames(machine_bmi))
 
 #Convert response variable to factor
 machine_bmi$res_set <- as.factor(machine_bmi$res_set)
 machine_bmi <- na.omit(machine_bmi)
 
 #Reproducibility
 set.seed(8)
 
 #Random forest
 class_bmi<- randomForest(res_set ~ ., data= machine_bmi, ntree=1000, importance= TRUE)
 print(class_bmi)
